</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Factorising Quadratic Expressions</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>A quadratic experssion has the form ax<SUP>2</SUP> + bx + c.  In some cases this expression can be factorised i.e., it can be written as a product of two linear factors:</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">(px+q)(rx+s)</P>
<br>
<P>If the expression has the form x<SUP>2</SUP> + bx + c (i.e. if a=1) then its factorised form will be </P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">(x+q)(x+s)</P>
<P>where q, s can be positive or negative numbers.  Work through Lesson 1-21 <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 21 a 0~?">section a</a>, 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 21 b 0~?">section b</a>, and  
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 21 d 0~?">section d</a> to remind yourself how to find the values of q and s.</P>

<P>Now consider the more general case of factorising an expression with a>1 or a<1.  Work through Lesson 1-21 <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 21 e 0~?">section e</a>, and 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 21 f 0~?">section f</a>.</P>

<P>Finally, practise factorising quadratic expressions by answering questions
<a href="launch.htm#q0021">q0021</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0120">q0120</a>.</P> 

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>This is the <B>end</B> of the Learning Plan on Factorisation.</P>
